  • Q10: Does age present a significant effect on medv in this model?

Clearly not!

Lets calculate the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) of each predictor in the above full model. VIF of a predictor \(X_j\) measures how well \(X_j\) can be represented as a linear combination of other predictors used in the model. A high VIF indicates that the predictor has a high multicollinearity with other predictors, thus should probably be excluded from the set of predictors to improve the model fit. VIF of a predictor \(X_j\) is calculated by the formula \(\text{VIF}_j = \frac{1}{1-R_j^2}\), where \(R_j^2\) is the R-Square value of the model fit by using \(X_j\) as the response variable and all other predictors used in the original model as predictors. For instance, to calculate the VIF of age in the context of lm.fit.full model:

(VIF_age <- 1/(1-summary(lm(age ~ .-medv, data = Boston))$r.sq))
[1] 3.100826

Note that in the above line, lm(age ~ .-medv, data=Boston) means to fit a linear model for age using all columns of Boston but medv.

We can use the vif function in the car package to calculate the VIF for all predictors in a model, as follows.

#install.packages("car")  # run this line if you have not installed the "car" package before
library(car)
Loading required package: carData
vif(lm.fit.full)

# Set up repeated k-fold cross-validation

# Train the model
step.model11 <- train(medv ~ . - age, data = Boston,
                    method = "leapBackward", 
                    tuneGrid = data.frame(nvmax = 1:12),
                    trControl = train.control
                    )

False: The Interaction Effect is there. The scale of it is small but not negligebale. Lets transform the model to hightlight the interaction between IQ and GPA:

\(\text{salary} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \text{GPA} + \hat{\beta}_3 \cdot \text{Gender } + (\hat{\beta}_2 + \hat{\beta}_4 \cdot \text{GPA}) \cdot \text{IQ} \cdot + \hat{\beta}_5 \cdot (\text{GPA} \cdot \text{Gender})\)

The increase of GPA by one adds a ~ 1% of itself to the acceleration of the grow of the IQ.

Problem 4:

a)

The training RSS for polynomial regression model will be smaller then RSS for linear regression model: greater flexibility allows to find closer fit.

b)

The testing RSS for polynomial regression model may be greater then testing RSS for linear regression model: greater flexibility may yeild residuals where there must be none cause the true fit is linear.

c)

The training RSS for polynomial regression model will be smaller then RSS for linear regression model.

d)

The testing RSS for polynomial regression model will be smaller then testing RSS for linear regression model: greater flexibility will minimize residuals cause the true fit is non-linear in the test data.
